title: ‘Typical Russian lies’: Zelensky rejects Putin estate strike
description: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenski states the Russian President Vladimir Putin's strike narrative is a complete fabrication meant to rationalise further assaults on Ukraine.  “Russia is at it again, using dangerous statements to undermine all achievements of our shared diplomatic efforts,” Mr Zelenski said.  “This alleged residence strike story is a complete fabrication intended to justify additional attacks against Ukraine.  “Typical Russian lies.”

title: ‘We’ll knock the hell out of them’: Trump warns Iran is trying to build up again
description: US President Donald Trump discusses Iran building up their defence and how America would retaliate.   “Now I hear that Iran is trying to build up again,” Mr Trump said.  “If they are, we’re going to have to knock them down … we’ll knock the hell out of them.  “They should make a deal.”

title: Flu cases surge from a new strain of Influenza A
description: Deakin University Chair Prof Catherine Bennett warns about a new strain of influenza A and increased activity.  “A particular strain of influenza A … seems to have acquired some mutations,” Ms Bennett said.   “Having any kind of respiratory illness in summer just feels so much worse.”  More than 95,000 infections have been recorded in the state this year.

title: Trump hosts his ‘friend’ Netanyahu at Mar-a-Lago
description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu praises his “friend,” US President Donald Trump, at Mar-a-Lago.  “We've never had a friend, even a close friend, as President Trump and the White House,” Mr Netanyahu said.  “He's been extraordinary in his friendship and support for Israel.”

title: Israel ‘we’re with you’: Trump
description: US President Donald Trump claims the “wartime” leaders have peace in the Middle East, following a meeting wth Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.  “We’re with you, and we will continue to be with you,” Mr Trump said.  “We have peace in the Middle East.”

title: Israel awards prize to Donald Trump
description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu awards the “Israel Prize” to US President Donald Trump for his “tremendous contributions”.  “President Trump has broken so many conventions to the surprise of people … so we decided to break a convention too,” Mr Netanyahu said.  “In almost 80 years, we’ve never awarded it to a non-Israeli.”

title: A partnership ‘second to none’: US-Israel
description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu meets US President Donald Trump at Mar-a-Lago, where the world leaders discussed a partnership “second to none”.  “It’s allowed us to do enormous things … we work together,” Mr Netanyahu said.  “This was a very productive meeting.  “Thank you for your friendship and thank you for your support.”

title: Trump warns Hamas to disarm or else there'll be ‘hell to pay’
description: US President Donald Trump says there'll be “hell to pay” if Hamas does not disarm, following a meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at Mar-a-Lago.  “They’re going to be given a very short period of time to disarm,” Mr Trump said.  “If you don't disarm as they agreed to do, then there'll be hell to pay.”

title: ‘Serious things happened’: Celebrity chef on his decision to close Jewish bakery
description: ‘Avner’s’ Bakery owner Ed Halmagyi discusses his decision to shut down his bakery after the recent Bondi Beach terror attack.   “The business has for two years non-stop … with all manner of graffiti, vandalism, broken windows, glue in the door locks, threatening notes under the door, people screaming abuse out the window of a passing car,” Mr Halmagyi told Sky News Australia.   “Along the way, there were more serious things that happened.”

title: Riot squad to carry long-arm weapons at NYE celebrations
description: New South Wales Police Commissioner Mal Lanyon announces that the Australian public order and riot squad will be carrying long-arm weapons whilst working the NYE celebrations.   “NSW police will implement the most comprehensive security regime that it has over New Year's Eve,” Mr Lanyon said.  “Our public order and riot squad will be carrying long arms this year, that does not represent any specific threat.  “It is to provide reassurance to the community.”

title: ‘Police should be the first form of protection’: CSG asks for more resources
description: New South Wales Police Commissioner Mal Lanyon explains the CSG’s role in protecting Jewish communities.  “The premier and the government haven’t made a decision in terms of CSG and their powers,” Mr Lanyon said.  “We work very closely with the CSG and Jewish leaders.  “The police should be the first form of protection and security for all of the community.”

title: ‘Disgusting’: Thousands of backpackers leave behind rubbish at iconic beach on Christmas
description: Sky News host Freya Leach reacts to backpackers “descending” onto Coggee beach on Christmas Day.  “Thousands of backpackers went down to Coggee,” Ms Leach said.   “The amount of garbage that they left behind is genuinely disgusting.”

title: Renewed search for Malaysia Airlines flight MH370 to resume
description: A renewed search for Malaysia Airlines flight MH370 is expected to begin on Tuesday, nearly 12 years after the plane disappeared.  The search will include a newly identified 15,000-square-kilometre zone believed to be the best chance of finding the aircraft.  The Malaysian government has promised $70 million to the private marine robotics company Ocean Infinity if they manage to find the plane.

title: Judge rules transcript from closed-door Tyler Robinson hearing can be released
description: The judge assigned to the trial of the alleged assassin of conservative commentator Charlie Kirk has made two new rulings relating to how much of the case the public will be able to see.  Judge Tony Graf has agreed to release a redacted transcript from a closed-door hearing back in October.  The transcript is expected to be released within the next day, whereas the audio recording is said to be released sometime in the next two weeks.

title: NSW Royal Commission to examine ‘creeping rise of antisemitism’: Minns
description: New South Wales Premier Chris Minns believes a state-level Royal Commission will examine the “sequence” of antisemitism, leading up to the Bondi massacre.  “I do believe it's an important opportunity to be looking at the circumstances and sequence that led up to this horrifying attack at Bondi,” Mr Minns said.  “You can’t have an investigation without an examination of the creeping rise of antisemitism.”
